@541    = ~ROGUE:

To accomplish his goals, for good or ill, the rogue is a skilled pilferer. Cunning, nimbleness, and stealth are his hallmarks. Whether he turns his talent against innocent passers-by and wealthy merchants or oppressors and monsters is a choice for the rogue to make.

Hit Points per Level: 1-6

Advantages:
* Proficient with all simple weapons, bows, and light armor.
* Rogues receive a larger number of skill points per level than any other character class. They can use these extra skill points to buy class skills like Disable Device to remove traps, Hide, Pick Pockets, and Use Magic Device.
* Sneak Attack: Rogues can sneak attack enemies to deal an additional 1d6 damage, plus 1d6 per 2 levels after level 1. An attack counts as a sneak attack if it hits an enemy in the back, if it occurs within 2 seconds of coming out of stealth or invisibility, or if the target is paralyzed, held, stunned, sleeping, confused, feebleminded, grappled, or feinted. Shortswords, throwing daggers, darts, shortbows, composite shortbows, light crossbows, slings, clubs and unarmed attacks deal an extra die of sneak attack damage. Melee daggers deal two extra dice of sneak attack damage.
* 2nd level: Evasion. When a rogue reaches 2nd level, he or she gains the ability to evade damage from area affect spells. Whenever a rogue makes a successful reflex save against an area effect spell that allows a reflex save for half damage, he or she takes no damage.
* 3rd level: Uncanny Dodge. Rogues retain their Dexterity bonus to Armor Class if they are attacked by invisible foes.
* 6th level: Improved Uncanny Dodge. Rogues can't be Sneak Attacked by another rogue unless the attacker is higher level.
* 8th level: Disarm Complex Traps. Rogues of this level or higher are the only characters who can disarm traps with a DC of 20 or higher.
* 10th level: Bonus Feat. The rogue gains a bonus feat, and also gains access to a number of new feats available only to rogues. These include Crippling Strike, Improved Evasion, Slippery Mind, Defensive Roll, and Opportunist. The rogue gains another bonus feat every 3 levels after level 10.
* Rogues gain +1 to luck every 5 levels.

Disadvantages:
* Rogues have no spellcasting ability and poor toe-to-toe combat ability.~
@223    = ~Arterial Strike

While this ability is active, your sneak attacks deal 10 bleeding damage over 10 rounds. For every six rogue levels past 1 (i.e. at levels 7, 13, 19, and 25), you deal another 10 damage over the 10 rounds. This ability can be activated or deactivated at will as a free action., but it cannot be active at the same time as Hamstring.~
@224    = ~Hamstring

While this ability is active, your sneak attacks reduce the target's movement speed by 50% for 10 rounds (no save). Since this is a nonmagical effect, it bypasses Freedom of Movement. This ability can be activated or deactivated at will as a free action, but it cannot be active at the same time as Arterial Strike.~
@702    = ~ARTERIAL STRIKE:

Your skill with sneak attacks allows you to cause a bleeding wound.

Prerequisite: At least one level of rogue, base attack bonus +4 or higher.

Benefit: Gives the rogue an ability that causes their sneak attacks to inflict a bleeding wound that causes deals an extra 10 damage over 10 rounds. For every six rogue levels past 1 (i.e. at levels 7, 13, 19, and 25), the rogue deals another 10 damage over the 10 rounds. This ability cannot be active at the same time as Hamstring.~
@734    = ~HAMSTRING:

When making a sneak attack, your character can maim their target in such a way that their movement is significantly decreased.

Prerequisite: At least three levels of rogue.

Benefit:  Gives the rogue an ability that causes their sneak attacks to reduce the target's movement speed by 50% for 10 rounds. This is a nonmagical effect that bypasses Freedom of Movement. This ability cannot be active at the same time as Arterial Strike.~
@735    = ~POWER ATTACK:

You can make exceptionally powerful melee attacks.

Prerequisite: Str 13+

Benefit: On your action, before making attack rolls for a round, you may choose to subtract a number from all melee attack rolls and add the same number to all melee damage rolls, or twice that number if you are wielding a two-handed weapon. This number may not exceed your base attack bonus. The penalty on attacks and bonus on damage apply until your next action.~
@977    = ~Barbarian Rage

By entering a rage, the barbarian gains +4 to Strength and Constitution (which stack with other bonuses to Strength and Constitution), as well as a -2 AC penalty, +2 to Will saves, and immunity to fear, stun, sleep, charm, domination, confusion, unconsciousness, paralysis, feeblemind, and hopelessness. The rage lasts for 3 rounds. If the character has at least 5 barbarian levels, the rage also lasts a number of additional rounds equal to the barbarian's (newly improved) Constitution bonus. After raging the barbarian will be fatigued for three rounds, giving them a -2 penalty to Strength and Dexterity.~
@525    = ~BARBARIAN:

From the frozen wastes of the north and the hellish jungles of the south come brave, even reckless, warriors. While not as disciplined or as skilled as a normal fighter, the barbarian can willingly throw himself into a berserker rage, becoming a tougher and stronger opponent.

Hit points per level: 1-12

Advantages:
* Proficient with all simple and martial weapons, light armor, medium armor, and shields.
* Barbarian Rage: Can rage once per day per every 4 levels (starts at 1st level with one use). Rage gives them +4 to Strength and Constitution (which stack with other bonuses to Strength and Constitution), as well as a -2 AC penalty, +2 to Will saves, and immunity to fear, stun, sleep, charm, domination, confusion, unconsciousness, paralysis, feeblemind, and hopelessness for 3 rounds. After raging the barbarian will be fatigued for three rounds, giving them a -2 penalty to Strength and Dexterity.
* Fast Movement: Barbarians can move 10 feet faster than a standard character, provided they are not encumbered or wearing heavy armor.
* 2nd level: Damage Reduction. The barbarian gains 1/- point of resistance to slashing, piercing, and bludgeoning damage. He or she gains 1/- additional point of resistance at levels 5, 8, 11, and every 3 levels thereafter. If the barbarian wears medium armor, the damage reduction granted by this feature is doubled.
* 2nd level: Uncanny Dodge. Barbarians retain their Dexterity bonus to Armor Class if they are attacked by invisible foes.
* 5th level: Improved Uncanny Dodge. Barbarians cannot be Sneak Attacked by rogues unless the attacker is higher level than the barbarian. Barbarian rage now lasts a number of additional rounds equal to the barbarian's newly improved Constitution bonus.
* 11th level: Greater Rage. All of the barbarian's rages become greater rages, which increase the Strength and Constitution bonuses to +6 and the Will save bonus to +3. He or she still receives the -2 AC penalty.
* 17th level: Tireless Rage. The barbarian is no longer fatigued after a rage.
* 20th level: Mighty Rage. The barbarian's rage ability now grants +8 to Strength and Constitution and +4 to Will saves. For every 4 levels after level 20, barbarian rage will grant an additional +2 to Strength and Constitution and +1 to Will saves.
* 21st level: Limitless Strength. The barbarian can now increase their Strength past 40.

Disadvantages:
* Barbarians gain feats at a slower rate than fighters.
* Barbarians do not start with proficiency in heavy armor.~
@527    = ~BARD:

The bard's strength is his pleasant and charming personality. With it and his wits he makes his way through the world. A bard is a talented musician and a walking storehouse of gossip, tall tales, and lore. He learns a little bit about everything that crosses his path; he is a jack-of-all-trades but master of none. While many bards are scoundrels, their stories and songs are welcome almost everywhere.

Hit Points per Level: 1-6

Advantages:
* Proficient with all simple weapons, light armor, medium armor, and shields. The bard is also proficient with large swords.
* Gains one point in Armored Arcana, reducing arcane spell failure by 35%.
* +1 to Alchemy, Knowledge (Arcana) and Spellcraft.
* 2nd level: Spellcasting. Bards gain the ability to cast arcane spells.
* Many rogue like skills are class skills of the Bard.
* Bard Songs. Bards have the ability to sing melodies that have magical effects on creatures within thirty feet. As they advance in level, they gain additional songs. The songs are described in detail below.
* 1st level: The Tale of Curran Strongheart. When played, all the bard's allies gain +1 attack bonus, +1 damage, and immunity to fear and hopelessness. The attack and damage bonuses increase by 1 at level 5 and every 5 levels thereafter.
* 3th level: The Song of Kaudies. When played, the bard's allies are immune to harmful sound-based spells and abilities, including Command, Silence, Greater Command, Holy Word, Blasphemy, Power Word: Sleep, Sound Burst, Shout, Power Word: Silence, Power Word: Stun, Power Word: Blind, Great Shout, Wail of the Banshee, Power Word: Kill, Void Sound, harpy wails, and the enemy-only effects of Chant, Prayer, and Recitation.
* 5th level: Tymora's Melody. When played, Tymora's Melody gives the bard's allies +1 luck, and +2 to skill checks (in addition to the +1 to skill checks granted by the luck). At level 15 and every 10 levels thereafter, this song grants an additional +1 to luck and +2 to skill checks.
* 7th level: The bard may replace one of their known spells with another spell of the same level. They may do this once again every 3 levels after level 7. The bard can only replace spells at least two spell levels below the highest spell level they can cast (e.g. only a 1st-level spell when the bard reaches 7th level), though they can replace 7th-level spells starting at level 25, and 8th-level spells starting at level 28.
* 9th level: The Siren's Yearning. When played, every enemy that hears the song must make a Will save or be enthralled, unable to take action for one round or until they take damage. The Will save DC is equal to 10 + 1/2 bard level + Charisma bonus.
* 13th level: The War Chant of Sith. When played, the bard's allies gain a +2 generic armor bonus, physical damage resistance of 3/-, and they regenerate 3 points of damage per round in combat. At level 18 and every 10 levels thereafter, this song grants an additional +2 to AC, 3/- physical damage resistance, 3 hit points healed per round.
* 40th level: The Ballad of Three Heroes. When played, the bard's allies gain 10/- resistance to all forms of magical damage, spell resistance set to 35 if lower, and the effects of the Tale of Curran Strongheart, Tymora's Melody, and the War Chant of Sith. At level 50, this song sets spell resistance to 40 if lower and grants another 10/- resistance to magical damage.

A bard cannot benefit the party with more than one song at once. But if the party has multiple bards, the effects of each bard's song will stack. Summoned creatures do not benefit from bard songs.

* 30th level: The bard can now do other actions while singing a bard song.

Disadvantages:
* Bards are not as effective in hand-to-hand combat as warriors or priests.
* Bards have slower access to spells than a wizard or priest.~
@535    = ~MONK:

Monks are warriors who pursue perfection through contemplation as well as action. They are versatile fighters, especially skilled in combat without weapons or armor. Though monks cannot cast spells, they have a unique magic of their own. They channel a subtle energy, called ki, which allows them to perform amazing feats. The monk's best-known feat is their ability to stun an opponent with an unarmed blow.

NOTE: Multiclassed monks ONLY use their monk levels when determining their number of attacks when fighting unarmed.

Hit Points per Level: 1-8

Advantages:
* The monk attacks at a faster rate than other characters while unarmed:

Level 1-3: 2 attacks per round
Level 4-6: 3 attacks
Level 7-9: 4 attacks
Level 10-12: 5 attacks
Level 13-15: 6 attacks. For every 3 levels after 13, the monk gains another attack per round.

* Monk Weapons: The monk can wield quarterstaves, daggers, throwing daggers, and darts with very few penalties (one fewer attack per round than with fists, but the monk will still get an extra attack per round every 3 levels).

* As the monk increases in levels, the damage their fists inflicts does as well:

Level 1-2: 1d6
Level 3-4: 1d8
Level 5-7: 1d8+1
Level 8-10: 1d8+2
Level 11-13: 1d8+3
Level 14-16: 1d8+4
Level 17+: 1d8+5

* Ki Strike: At level 5, the monk's unarmed attack is empowered with ki, and gains +1 enchantment with corresponding bonuses to attack and damage. This enchantment bonus increases by +1 every 3 levels after level 5, up to +5 at level 17.
* A monk's natural armor class starts at 10, and then increases by +1 at 5th level and every 5 levels thereafter.
* When not wearing armor (robes are acceptable) a monk adds their Wisdom bonus to their AC in the same manner as their Dexterity bonus. This bonus may not exceed the character's monk level.
* Stunning Attacks: When this ability is used, all of the monk's unarmed attacks in the next round force the victim to make a Fortitude save (DC 10 + Wisdom modifier + half the monk's level) or be stunned for 1 round. A monk can make a stunning attack 1/day/level.
* Evasion: Monks have the ability to evade damage from area of effect spells. Whenever a monk makes a successful Reflex save against an area effect spell that allows a reflex save for half damage, he or she takes no damage.
* 2nd level: Deflect Arrows. The monk gains the Deflect Arrows feat, yielding a +1 miscellanous bonus against missile weapons. In addition, the monk automatically blocks the first instance of missile damage that would hit them each round. The monk must have a hand free to block missiles this way.
* 3rd level: Fast Movement. The monk moves 10 feet faster than a normal character (normal movement speed is 30 feet), but only as long as the monk is not encumbered or wearing armor. The monk gains another 10 feet of movement every 3 levels thereafter.
* 3rd level: Still Mind. The monk gains a +2 bonus to saving throws against spells and effects from the Enchantment school.
* 5th level: Purity of Body. The monk gains control over their body's immune system. They gain immunity to all diseases.
* 7th level: Wholeness of Body. The monk can regain hit points equal to their monk level times their Wisdom modifier once each day per seven levels.
* 9th level: Improved Evasion. The monk gains the Improved Evasion feat that is normally only available to rogues.
* 10th level: Abundant Step. The monk may teleport to any location in sight once per day.
* 11th level: Diamond Body. The monk is in such control of their own metabolism that they gain immunity to poison of all kinds.
* 13th level: Diamond Soul. The monk gains spell resistance. Their spell resistance equals their level + 10. In order to affect the monk with a spell, a spellcaster must roll the monk's spell resistance or higher on 1d20 + the spellcaster's level.
* 15th level: Quivering Palm. This terrifying attack allows the monk to set up vibrations within the body of another creature that can be fatal. The next time the monk hits a creature with an unarmed attack, the target dies unless it makes a Fortitude saving throw (DC 10 + Wisdom modifier + half the monk's level). Constructs and undead cannot be affected. The monk gains an additional use of Quivering Palm every six levels thereafter.
* 19th level: Empty Body. The monk can assume an incorporeal state for 5 rounds a number of times a day equal to their level divided by 2. While incorporeal, the monk can move through walls, and half the attacks that hit the monk deal no physical damage. The monk's unarmed attacks will ignore armor and shield bonuses.
* 20th level: Perfect Self. The monk has tuned their body with skill and quasi-magical abilities to the point that they become a magical creature. They are forevermore treated as an outsider (extraplanar creature) rather than as a humanoid. For instance, charm person does not affect them. Additionally, the monk gains damage reduction 20/+1. This means that the monk ignores (instantly regenerates) the first 20 points of damage from any attack unless the damage is dealt by a weapon with a +1 enhancement bonus (or better), by a spell, or by a form of energy (fire, cold, etc.). As an outsider, a 20th level monk is subject to spells that repel enchanted creatures, such as protection from law.

Disadvantages:
* Loses many bonuses if wearing armor and/or using weapons.~
@391    = ~Lingering Damage~
@392    = ~LINGERING DAMAGE:

Your sneak attacks continue to deal damage even after you strike.

Prerequisite: Crippling Strike, 30 levels of rogue

Benefit: If you deal damage with a sneak attack, you deal the same damage to that enemy again one round later.~
@358    = ~METAMAGIC, QUICKEN SPELL:

You may quickly cast an extra spell each round.

Prerequisites: The ability to cast 5th-level spells.

Benefit: You gain the Quicken Spell ability, usable at will as a free action. Using it allows you to instantly cast a spell, even if you've already cast a spell for the round. The quickened spell takes up a spell slot four levels higher. Only one spell can be quickened per round.~
@963    = ~Quicken Spell

This metamagic allows you to instantly cast your next spell, even if you've already cast a spell for the round. It will take up a spell slot four levels higher. You may only quicken one spell per round. Metamagic abilities can be used as a free action any number of times per day.~
@731    = ~IMPROVED CRITICAL:

You are especially adept at causing critical hits.

Prerequisite: Base attack bonus +8 or higher.

Benefit: When determining criticals, the base threat range of the weapon being wielded is doubled. An axe will critically hit on a 19-20, a longsword on a 17-20, and a scimitar on a 15-20.~
@372    = ~MOBILITY:

You can dodge attacks particularly well while moving.

Prerequisites: Dex 13+, Dodge. Taking the feat a second time requires Dex 21+ and Spring Attack.

Benefit: While moving, you gain a +4 Armor Class bonus. This bonus is doubled against attacks of opportunity due to moving out of an enemy's weapon range.

When taken a second time, the feat prevents you from provoking any attacks of opportunity due to moving out of an enemy's weapon range.~
@736    = ~SNAKE BLOOD:

The taint of the yuan-ti runs in your veins.  No outward signs give away your heritage, but you are something more - or less - than entirely human.

Prerequisite: Human

Benefit: Your race changes to yuan-ti pureblood. This race has the following traits:

Favored Class: Ranger

Advantages:
* +2 Dexterity.
* +2 Intelligence.
* +2 Charisma.
* Spell resistance of 6 + character level.
* +1 dodge bonus against all creatures.
* +2 bonus on Fortitude saving throws against poison.
* +1 bonus on all Reflex saving throws.
* Free Blind-Fight feat after character creation.
* Entangle 1/Day.
* Hold Animal 1/Day.
* Charm Person 1/Day.
* Spook 1/Day.
* Darkness 1/Day.
* At will, can polymorph self into a giant viper. In this form, the character's attacks will poison the target on a failed Fortitude save. This form becomes more powerful as the character levels up. If the character uses a druid wildshape ability to turn into a giant viper, their druid level is doubled for purposes of determining the power of the form.
* Darkvision.

Disadvantages:
* -25% Experience Penalty: Yuan-ti purebloods are slightly more powerful and gain 25% less experience than other races.

Special: You may only take this feat as a 1st-level character.~
@930    = ~Entangle

When an Entangle spell is cast, it must be cast outside, otherwise it will not work and the spell is wasted. It causes vines to sprout forth from the ground to wrap, twist, and entwine any creatures in the area of effect, preventing movement. Creatures must make a Reflex save every round in order to move through the entangled area. The DC is 11 + half level + Charisma bonus. Entangled creatures can still perform normal actions but cannot move and suffer a -2 penalty to Armor Class and attack rolls, as well as a 50% chance of spell failure. All creatures within the area of effect who make their Reflex save move at half rate.~
@931    = ~Charm Person

This spell charms a single humanoid of man-size or smaller for 5 rounds. The person receives a Will save to avoid the effect; the DC is 11 + half level + Charisma bonus. If the spell recipient fails their saving throw, they regards the caster as a trusted friend and ally to be heeded and protected. The caster may give them orders, and the charmed individual will carry them out as quickly as possible.~
@932    = ~Spook

A Spook spell enables the wizard to play upon natural fears to cause the target creature to perceive the spellcaster as someone or something inimical which then appears to advance upon it in a threatening manner. If the creature does not make a successful Will save, it panics for 3 rounds. The base DC is 11 + Charisma bonus, though it also gets +1 for every two experience levels of the caster, to a maximum of +6 at 12th level. Although the caster does not actually pursue the fleeing creature, a phantasm from its own mind does. Spook does not affect undead or constructs.~
@933    = ~Hold Animal

This spell holds animals rigidly immobile. Animals with magical powers such as winter wolves do count as animals, as do some of the more animalistic monsters such as remorhazes. The effect is centered on a point selected by the caster, and 1-4 animals within 20 feet of the target point are affected. Those who succeed on their Will save are unaffected by the spell. The DC is 12 + half level + Charisma bonus. Being held does not prevent the worsening of the subject's condition due to wounds, disease, or poison.~
@934    = ~Polymorph: Giant Viper~
@935    = ~Polymorph: Giant Viper

The character shapeshifts into a giant viper. While in giant viper form, the character's attacks poison the target, dealing 2 damage per second for 6 seconds (Fortitude DC 15). At level 12 and every 3 levels thereafter, the giant viper form gains +1 to Strength, Dexterity and Constitution, +1 AC, and the save DC against its poison increases by 3.~
@971    = ~Darkness

This ability creates magical darkness in the area of effect. Creatures without darkvision must make a Fortitude saving throw or be effectively blinded. The DC is 12 + half level + Charisma bonus. Creatures with darkvision aren't blinded, but even they have only a limited ability to see through magical darkness, getting a -4 attack penalty on a failed save. Creatures with superior 120 foot darkvision (e.g. drow, gray dwarves or deep gnomes) only get a -2 attack penalty. Devils and creatures immune to blindness are unaffected.~
@393    = ~Arcane Archer~
@394    = ~ARCANE ARCHER:

You are trained as an arcane archer and know how to shoot spells as arrows.

Prerequisite: Elf or half-elf, 1 level of wizard or sorcerer, and proficiency in bows (if drow or half-elf)

Benefit: You gain the Imbue Arrow ability, usable as a free action. If you use it and then attempt to cast an offensive ranged wizard or sorcerer spell of 5th-level or lower that involves a projectile traveling from the caster, instead of being cast, it will be stored in an arrow that is created in an empty ammo slot (consuming a use of the spell). That arrow has an enchantment equal to the level of the spell. When fired, the arrow uses the same projectile and area of effect as the spell, and deals the physical damage of the arrow in addition to the effects of the spell (as if cast at the character's wizard or sorcerer level) to all creatures it hits. This ability can be used once per day, plus once more for every two points of base attack bonus.

However, your spells have -4 DC when cast without imbuing them.

Special: You may only take this feat as a 1st-level character.~
